In business, when a [[company (law)|company]] is threatened with [[takeover]], the '''crown jewel defense''' is a strategy in which the target company sells off its most attractive [[asset]]s to a friendly third party or spin off the valuable assets in a separate entity. Consequently, the unfriendly bidder is less attracted to the company assets. Other effects include dilution of holdings of the acquirer, making the takeover uneconomical to third parties, and adverse influence of current [[stock market|share prices]]. <ref>{{cite book|last=Auerbach|first=Alan J.|title=Mergers and acquisitions|year=1987|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=0-226-03209-4|pages=49–68|url=https://www.nber.org/books/auer87-1|author2=[[Richard S. Ruback]]|chapter=3 An Overview of Takeover Defenses}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}} ==See also== * [[Economics]] * [[Mergers and Acquisitions]] * [[Microeconomics]] * [[Takeover]] * [[Industrial organization]]
[[Category:Anti-competitive behaviour]] [[Category:Mergers and acquisitions]] {{industry-stub}}

A '''double inverted pendulum''' is the combination of the [[inverted pendulum]] and the [[double pendulum]]. The double inverted pendulum is unstable, meaning that it will fall down unless it is controlled in some way. The two main methods of controlling a double inverted pendulum are moving the base, as with the inverted pendulum, or by applying a torque at the pivot point between the two pendulums.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~pabbeel/cs287-fa09/readings/Tedrake-Aug09.pdf | title = Underactuated Robotics: Learning, Planning, and Control for Efficient and Agile Machines, Course Notes for MIT 6.832 | author = Russ Tedrake | publisher = [[University of California, Berkeley]] | date = 2009 | accessdate = 2011-10-05}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Inverted pendulum]] *[[Inertia wheel pendulum]] *[[Furuta pendulum]]
