{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Use British English|date=April 2018}} {{BLP sources|date=January 2011}} {{Infobox person |name = Michael Meeks |image = Michael_Meeks.jpg |caption = Michael Meeks at the [[OpenOffice.org]] conference 2007 in Barcelona, Spain |nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] |home_town = [[Cambridge, United Kingdom]] |birth_date = |birth_place = |callsign = mmeeks |website = http://www.gnome.org/~michael/ |occupation = Software developer for [[Collabora]] }}
'''Michael Meeks''' is a British [[software developer]]. He is primarily known for his work on [[GNOME]], [[OpenOffice.org]] and now [[LibreOffice]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}}. He has been a major contributor{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} to the GNOME project for a long time working on its infrastructure and associated applications, particularly [[CORBA]], [[Bonobo (GNOME)|Bonobo]], [[Nautilus (file manager)|Nautilus]] and GNOME accessibility.<ref name="TD1">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuxdeluxe.org/node/184 |title=Meek not geek&nbsp;— Interview with Michael Meeks of OpenOffice.org |last=James |first=Daniel |date=2007-05-07 |work=Tux Deluxe |publisher=Frank Pohlmann |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vUkqeqKr?url=http://www.tuxdeluxe.org/node/184 |archivedate=2011-01-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> He was hired as a [[Ximian]] developer by [[Nat Friedman]] and [[Miguel de Icaza]] in mid-2000 {{Citation needed|date=November 2014}}, continuing at [[Novell]], [[SuSE]] and then [[Collabora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.gnome.org/~michael/blog/2013-09-03-collabora.html|title=Collabora and LibreOffice|date=3 September 2013|accessdate=1 October 2013|first=Michael|last=Meeks|work=Stuff Michael Meeks is doing (blog)}}</ref>
Meeks is a [[free software]] [[Hacker (programmer subculture)|hacker]] who has contributed a lot of time to decreasing program load time.<ref name=lwn192624>{{cite web | url = https://lwn.net/Articles/192624 | last1 = Moser | first1 = John Richard | date = 2006 | title = Optimizing Linker Load Times}}</ref> He created the direct binding, hashvals, and dynsort implementations for [[GNU Binutils]] and [[glibc]].<ref name=lwn192624 /> Most of this work was focused at making OpenOffice.org and now its fork LibreOffice start faster,<ref name=lwn192624 /> and was later subsumed into the "-hash-style=gnu" [[Linker (computing)|linking]] [[Optimization (computer science)|optimization]]. His work on [[iogrind]] also allows applications to be profiled and optimized to first-time (or 'cold') start far more rapidly {{Citation needed|date=November 2014}}.
He supports [[LibreOffice]] and [[Evolution (software)|Evolution]] as the free software solutions for document editing and groupware.<ref name="ZDNet1">{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnetasia.com/oss-recommended-picks-for-business-users-62205320.htm |title=OSS recommended picks for business users |last=Kwang |first=Kevin |date=2010-12-23 |work=ZDNet |publisher=CBS Interactive |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vUngwKPA?url=http://www.zdnetasia.com/oss-recommended-picks-for-business-users-62205320.htm |archivedate=2011-01-04 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
Previously he worked for [[Quantel]] gaining expertise in real time AV editing and playback achieved with high performance focused hardware/software solutions.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}}
Meeks is a [[Christian]], which he says made him think about the moral aspects of his own illegal use of non-free software and converted him finally to free software.<ref name="TD1" />
