'''SMS ''Magdeburg''''' ("His Majesty's Ship ''Magdeburg''"){{efn|name=SMS|}} was a [[lead ship]] of the {{sclass-|Magdeburg|cruiser|4}} of [[light cruiser]]s in the German ''[[Kaiserliche Marine]]'' (Imperial Navy). Her class included three other ships: {{SMS|Breslau||2}}, {{SMS|Strassburg||2}}, and {{SMS|Stralsund||2}}. ''Magdeburg'' was built at the [[AG Weser]] shipyard in [[Bremen]] from 1910 to August 1912, when she was commissioned into the [[High Seas Fleet]]. The ship was armed with a main battery of twelve [[10.5 cm SK L/45 naval gun|10.5&nbsp;cm SK L/45 guns]] and had a top speed of {{convert|27.5|kn}}. ''Magdeburg'' was used as a torpedo test ship after her commissioning until the outbreak of [[World War I]] in August 1914, when she was brought to active service and deployed to the [[Baltic Sea|Baltic]].

In the Baltic, ''Magdeburg'' fired the first shots of the war against the Russians on 2 August, when she shelled the port of [[Liepāja|Libau]]. She participated in a series of bombardments of Russian positions until late August. On the 26th, she participated in a sweep of the entrance to the [[Gulf of Finland]]; while steaming off the Estonian coast, she ran aground off the island of [[Odensholm]] and could not be freed. A pair of Russian cruisers appeared and seized the ship. Fifteen crew members were killed in the brief engagement. They recovered three intact German code books, one of which they passed to the British. The ability to decrypt German wireless signals provided the British with the ability to ambush German units on several occasions during the war, including the [[Battle of Jutland]]. The Russians partially scrapped ''Magdeburg'' while she remained grounded before completely destroying the wreck.

==Design==
{{main|Magdeburg class cruiser}}

''Magdeburg'' was ordered under the contract name "''[[Ersatz]]'' {{SMS|Bussard||2}}"{{efn|name=provisional names}} and was laid down at the [[AG Weser]] shipyard in [[Bremen]] in 1910 and launched on 13 May 1911, after which [[fitting-out]] work commenced. She was commissioned into the [[High Seas Fleet]] on 20 August 1912.<ref name=G107>Gröner, p. 107</ref> The ship was {{convert|138.7|m|sp=us}} [[length overall|long overall]] and had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|13.5|m|abbr=on}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|4.4|m|abbr=on}} forward. She displaced {{convert|4570|t|abbr=on}} at full combat load.<ref name=G108>Gröner, p. 108</ref> Her propulsion system consisted of two sets of [[AEG]]-Vulcan [[steam turbine]]s driving two {{convert|3.4|m|adj=on|sp=us}} propellers. They were designed to give {{convert|25000|shp|lk=in}}, but reached {{convert|33482|shp|abbr=on}} in service. These were powered by sixteen coal-fired Marine-type [[water-tube boiler]]s, although they were later altered to use [[fuel oil]] that was sprayed on the coal to increase its burn rate. These gave the ship a top speed of {{convert|27.5|kn}}. ''Magdeburg'' carried {{convert|1200|t|LT}} of coal, and an additional {{convert|106|t|LT}} of oil that gave her a range of approximately {{convert|5820|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn}}. She had a crew of 18 officers and 336 enlisted men.<ref name=G1078>Gröner, pp. 107–108</ref>

The ship was armed with twelve [[10.5 cm SK L/45 naval gun|10.5&nbsp;cm SK L/45 guns]] in single pedestal mounts. Two were placed side by side forward on the [[forecastle]], eight were located amidships, four on either side, and two were side by side aft.<ref name=C159>Gardiner & Gray, p. 159</ref> The guns had a maximum elevation of 30&nbsp;degrees, which allowed them to engage targets out to {{convert|12700|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>Gardiner & Gray, p. 140</ref> They were supplied with 1,800 rounds of ammunition, for 150 shells per gun. She was also equipped with a pair of {{convert|50|cm|abbr=on|1}} [[torpedo tube]]s with five [[torpedo]]es submerged in the hull on the [[broadside]]. She could also carry 120 [[naval mine|mines]]. The ship was protected by a waterline [[armored belt]] that was {{convert|60|mm|abbr=on}} thick amidships. The [[conning tower]] had {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on}} thick sides, and the deck was covered with up to 60&nbsp;mm thick armor plate.<ref name=G107/>

==Service history==
After her commissioning, ''Magdeburg'' was used as a torpedo test ship. Following the outbreak of [[World War I]] in August 1914, she was assigned to the [[Baltic Sea]],<ref name=G107/> under the command of Rear Admiral [[Robert Mischke]]. ''Magdeburg'' fired the first shots of the war with Russia on 2 August when she shelled the Russian port of [[Liepāja|Libau]] while {{SMS|Augsburg||2}} laid a minefield outside the harbor. The Russians had in fact already left Libau, which was seized by the German Army. The minefield laid by ''Augsburg'' was poorly marked and hindered German operations more than Russian efforts. ''Magdeburg'' and the rest of the Baltic forces then conducted a series of bombardments of Russian positions, including one ten days later, on 12 August, where ''Magdeburg'' shelled the [[Kalana, Hiiu County|Dagerort]] [[Ristna Lighthouse|lighthouse]]. On 17 August, ''Magdeburg'', ''Augsburg'', three [[destroyer]]s, and the [[minelayer]] {{SMS|Deutschland|1914|2}} encountered a pair of powerful Russian [[armored cruiser]]s, {{ship|Russian cruiser|Admiral Makarov|1906|2}} and {{ship|Russian cruiser|Gromoboi||2}}. The Russian commander, under the mistaken assumption that the German armored cruisers {{SMS|Roon||2}} and {{SMS|Prinz Heinrich||2}} were present, did not attack and both forces withdrew.<ref name=H184>Halpern, p. 184</ref>

[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 134-B2501, Kleiner Kreuzer Magdeburg.jpg|thumb|''Magdeburg'' aground off [[Odensholm]]]]
[[Prince Henry of Prussia (1862–1929)|Prince Heinrich]], the overall commander of the Baltic naval forces, replaced Mischke with Rear Admiral Behring. Behring ordered another operation for 26 August to sweep for Russian reconnaissance forces in the entrance to the [[Gulf of Finland]]. Early that morning, ''Magdeburg'' ran aground off the lighthouse at [[Odensholm]] on the Estonian coast. Her escorting destroyer, {{SMS|V.26||2}}, attempted to pull her free but was unable to do so and began taking off part of ''Magdeburg''{{'}}s crew. While the evacuation was going on, the Russian cruisers {{ship|Russian cruiser|Bogatyr||2}} and {{ship|Russian cruiser|Pallada|1906|2}} appeared and shelled the stranded cruiser.<ref name=H184/> The Germans destroyed the forward section of the ship, but could not complete her destruction before the Russians reached the ship.<ref>Halpern, p. 185</ref> Fifteen crew members from ''Magdeburg'' were killed in the attack.<ref name=G107/> The German code books were also not destroyed; the Russians were able to recover three of the books along with the current encryption key. They passed one copy to the British [[Royal Navy]] via a pair of Russian couriers on 13 October.<ref>Halpern, p. 36</ref> The Russian Navy partially scrapped the ship [[in situ]] and eventually destroyed the wreck.<ref name=G107/>

The capture of the code books proved to provide a significant advantage for the Royal Navy. The [[Admiralty]] had recently created a deciphering department known as [[Room 40]] to process intercepted German wireless signals. With the code books and cipher key, the British were able to track the movements of most German warships; this information could be passed on to the Admiral [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|John Jellicoe]], the commander of the [[Grand Fleet]].<ref>Herwig, p. 150</ref> This allowed the British to ambush parts of or the entire German fleet on several occasions, most successfully at the Battles of [[Battle of Dogger Bank (1915)|Dogger Bank]] in January 1915 and [[Battle of Jutland|Jutland]] in May 1916.<ref>Herwig, pp. 151, 178</ref>

